WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.160
Hi, I'm Maria Vendettuoli. I'm a Senior Statistical Programmer at Fred Hutch in the Statistical

00:00:11.160 --> 00:00:16.920
Center for HIV AIDS Research and Prevention. At RStudioCon 2020, my colleague Ellis Hughes

00:00:16.920 --> 00:00:20.959
shared technical details demonstrating how our organization is tackling the challenge

00:00:20.959 --> 00:00:26.600
of software validation for R packages. It's now a year later. We have three packages released

00:00:26.600 --> 00:00:30.080
and are tackling the extended challenge of ensuring that our entire verse is fit for

00:00:30.080 --> 00:00:34.459
purpose as an integrated unit. Today, I'll be sharing my thoughts regarding multi-package

00:00:34.459 --> 00:00:38.720
development in the pharma environment. My first recommendation is to set the team up

00:00:38.720 --> 00:00:43.840
for success by getting infrastructure in order. Moving away from historical validation practices

00:00:43.840 --> 00:00:49.680
means updating or generating new SOPs. Another area for infrastructure support is to establish

00:00:49.680 --> 00:00:54.400
common development guidelines that get shared across all packages. This is especially important

00:00:54.400 --> 00:00:59.799
if packages are implementing legacy code that was previously siloed. The ultimate benefit,

00:00:59.799 --> 00:01:04.519
however, is code portability within the overall project. My next recommendation is the need

00:01:04.519 --> 00:01:09.440
to address development from an empathy perspective. At SHARP, we observe four distinct roles.

00:01:09.440 --> 00:01:14.639
One, users rapidly processing data. These would be primarily statistical programmers.

00:01:14.639 --> 00:01:19.519
Two, data analysts reviewing code for context. These would be individuals who need to be

00:01:19.519 --> 00:01:25.120
able to rapidly assess context from function names alone. Three, stakeholders interacting

00:01:25.120 --> 00:01:29.120
with functions solely from the package validation report. So, this could be someone involved

00:01:29.120 --> 00:01:36.199
in writing specifications and test cases but aren't participating in coding activity. Four,

00:01:36.199 --> 00:01:40.519
package developers and maintainers who seek to eliminate duplication or re-implementation

00:01:40.519 --> 00:01:44.680
with package updates. Now, one common need that transcends all of these user groups is

00:01:44.680 --> 00:01:49.360
to have a vocabulary which allows us to place functions within the larger context of assay-specific

00:01:49.360 --> 00:01:54.720
data processing tasks. That is, we want to survey what has been implemented, filter either

00:01:54.720 --> 00:02:00.519
by assay or task, and call up help page documentation on demand. So, this is actually a reference

00:02:00.519 --> 00:02:05.360
to Schneiderman's information-seeking mantra, which is typically cited in visualization

00:02:05.360 --> 00:02:09.639
literature. In this context, we are treating the function names as the identifying handle

00:02:09.639 --> 00:02:14.240
and leveraging RStudio's autocomplete as the filtering mechanism as we navigate to

00:02:14.240 --> 00:02:19.360
a particular help page or call the function. For example, one step of data processing that

00:02:19.360 --> 00:02:24.600
occurs for all assays is the transformation to a CDISC Atom basic data structure. Because

00:02:24.600 --> 00:02:29.320
of the function naming convention we have chosen, a list of all available BDS transformation

00:02:29.320 --> 00:02:33.360
functions are displayed and we can select for the assay of interest.

00:02:33.360 --> 00:02:37.119
Focusing on the package validation elements, we also need a systematic approach to how

00:02:37.119 --> 00:02:42.720
we map package requirements, test cases, and test code files. Validation is a form of user

00:02:42.720 --> 00:02:46.520
acceptance testing, where we have to show that for every software requirement there

00:02:46.520 --> 00:02:51.600
was an appropriate test successfully executed. The modular approach we use at SHARP is incredibly

00:02:51.600 --> 00:02:55.639
flexible, which has the development benefits I will discuss later, but it does require

00:02:55.639 --> 00:03:00.600
some organization to track. In addition to enforcing a file naming convention, we also

00:03:00.600 --> 00:03:05.679
scrape these files to generate a tabular display in the validation report, which links requirements

00:03:05.679 --> 00:03:11.199
and tests. Between these two implementations, both developers and validation report stakeholders

00:03:11.199 --> 00:03:15.039
are able to verify at a glance that complete coverage exists.

00:03:15.039 --> 00:03:20.479
The last couple recommendations I have address the topic of technical debt. You may be wondering,

00:03:20.479 --> 00:03:25.839
why are we splitting assays into separate packages? A couple reasons. First, FDA guidance

00:03:25.839 --> 00:03:31.800
asks us to revalidate the entire system when one element changes. Now, change is expected,

00:03:31.800 --> 00:03:37.119
input data structures get updated, analysis needs drift. However, an update to one assay

00:03:37.160 --> 00:03:42.479
type should not introduce the appearance of change affecting other assays. Secondly, from

00:03:42.479 --> 00:03:47.399
the user perspective, we need to put some conceptual structures around processes. Sure,

00:03:47.399 --> 00:03:51.839
every data set will be converted to BDS, but the definition of that basic data structure

00:03:51.839 --> 00:03:56.160
will vary from assay to assay, and we need to capture that distinction in a manner that

00:03:56.160 --> 00:04:01.759
is easy to digest. What we also want to avoid is excessive re-implementation. As we have

00:04:01.759 --> 00:04:06.960
expanded to multiple assay packages, we have identified utility functions that can be shared

00:04:06.960 --> 00:04:11.759
and moved into their own foundation package. We can enforce package code dependencies through

00:04:11.759 --> 00:04:16.559
routine use of the description file, but the power of modular validation means that we

00:04:16.559 --> 00:04:22.399
can move the associated specifications, test cases, and test code files as well. Validation

00:04:22.399 --> 00:04:27.279
of the lighter assay package with the new utility package is simply compiling the R

00:04:27.279 --> 00:04:32.640
markdown document without any need to rewrite content. Likewise, when we need to add additional

00:04:32.640 --> 00:04:38.000
specifications, test cases, or test code to an existing package, an updated validation

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:43.679
report will add the new child documents to existing sources. This has the added benefit

00:04:43.679 --> 00:04:48.959
of being able to use a simple diff to compare validation reports across package versions.

00:04:50.239 --> 00:04:53.920
So, I wanted to take a moment to thank those who made this work possible, especially the

00:04:53.920 --> 00:04:57.679
preceding efforts by Ellis Hughes and the combined contribution of the SHARP pData

00:04:57.679 --> 00:05:02.399
standardization team. Future work includes formalizing our validation practice

00:05:02.399 --> 00:05:11.920
through a FUSE-ORG collaboration with deliverables expected later in 2021.

